Gemini said
If you’re looking to grab the output of the previous command without reaching for your mouse or re-typing everything, there isn't a single "standard" keyboard shortcut (like Ctrl+C) that does this instantly in a raw Bash shell.

However, there are a few very fast ways to achieve this depending on your specific needs.

1. The "Standard" Way: Command Substitution
The most common way to pull the last output into a new command is to use Command Substitution. In Bash, the special variable !! represents the entire last command.

The Syntax: $(!!)

Example: * You run: which python (Output: /usr/bin/python)

You type: ls -l $(!!)

Bash executes: ls -l /usr/bin/python

2. The "Pro" Way: Shell Expansion (Alt + _ or ESC then .)
While this usually pulls the last argument of the previous command, it’s often what people are actually looking for.

Hotkey: Alt + . (or ESC then .)

What it does: Inserts the last word of the previous command into your current cursor position.

3. The "Pure Bash" Hotkey (Readline)
If you want a dedicated hotkey to insert the output of a command into your line as you are typing, you can use the shell-expand-line feature, but it requires a specific sequence:

Type your command: ls -l 

Type the substitution: $(!!)

Press: Ctrl + Alt + e

Result: Bash will immediately expand $(!!) into the actual output text on your command line before you even hit Enter.

Summary Table
Method	Key Combo / Command	Best Used For...
Command Substitution	$(!!)	Running a new command using the old output.
Last Argument	Alt + .	Grabbing a file path or name from the previous line.
Expand in Place	Ctrl + Alt + e	Seeing the output on your line before executing.
Quick Tip: If you find yourself doing this often to handle files, consider using the tool fzf (fuzzy finder). It allows you to bind a hotkey (usually Ctrl + T) to search and paste file paths directly into your command line.

